e its while loop after the await completes and will pick up the new idle worker on the next iteration.\n\nThe guard approach handles the main cases: if the queue empties, submit() will trigger a fresh processQueue call, and if workers become available while the guard is active, the while loop will catch them on the next iteration. There's an edge case where a new item arrives between the queue check and the return, but submit() handles that by calling processQueue directly. Similarly, when the while loop exits due to no idle workers, the 'worker-ready' event will trigger a new processQueue call once the guard is released.\n\nActually, I think the simplest fix is to use a flag that tracks whether we're currently dispatching, and if someone tries to call processQueue while that flag is set, we just set a \"needs recheck\" flag instead. Then after the current dispatch finishes, we check that flag and re-enter the loop if needed.\n\nSetting up a dispatching flag... I see the issue now—when a worker becomes available during the finally block, processQueue gets called but the guard rejects it, so that newly idle worker sits unused until the next item arrives. The real problem is that race condition between the finally block releasing the guard and a worker-ready event firing, where processQueue might get called but find nothing to do, leaving work stranded in the queue. called → dispatching is still true (about to be set to false) → rejected\n4. dispatching set to false\n5. Now there's an idle worker and items in queue but no one calls processQueue\n\nActually wait, JavaScript is single-threaded. The finally block runs synchronously. Between `this.dispatching = false` and the function returning, no event handler can fire. But after the function returns and control returns to the event loop, the next queued microtask/macrotask will run. So:\n\nStep 1: processQueue runs, while loop exits (no idle worker)\nStep 2: `finally { this.dispatching = false; }` runs\nStep 3: Function returns\nStep 4: Event loop picks up next task\n\nIf a 'worker-ready' event was queued during step 1's await, it would have been processed during that await (since events are emitted synchronously). So the event handler ran processQueue, which was blocked by the guard. After step 3, no new call to processQueue is pending.\n\nBut here's the issue: the while loop checks for idle workers before awaiting the dispatch. So if a worker becomes ready during the await, the loop's condition check already happened. Let me trace through the actual loop logic—it gets an idle worker, shifts an item from the queue, then awaits the dispatch. If the worker becomes ready during that await and triggers processQueue, the guard blocks it. Then when the loop resumes after the await, it checks for idle workers again, but by then dispatching is still true, so the guard still blocks any new processQueue call.\n\nThe real problem is that a worker-ready event during the await doesn't get a chance to run processQueue after the current iteration completes, because dispatching is still true until the finally block executes.\n\nI'm realizing the guard mechanism might not be sufficient—there could be a race where items stay queued even though workers are available. await: submit() called with new item → calls processQueue → blocked by guard\n5. await completes, while loop continues\n6. Queue has 1 item (from step 4), checks getIdleWorker() → returns the new worker from step 3\n7. Dispatches to it\n8. While loop: queue empty → exit\n\nThis works! The while loop naturally handles it.\n\nBut what about:\n1. Queue has 1 item, 1 idle worker\n2. processQueue starts, dispatches\n3. During await: new item submitted → processQueue blocked by guard\n4. await completes, while loop: queue has 1 item, getIdleWorker() → null (no workers free yet) → return\n5. Guard released\n6. Later, worker finishes → complete event → processQueue called → runs, picks up the queued item\n\nThis scenario also works correctly—