eaded). So:\n\n1. While loop exits (queue empty, or no idle worker)\n2. Finally block: dispatching = false\n3. Function returns\n4. Event loop processes next task\n\nIf during step 1's last await, a new item was submitted and a worker became ready, both their processQueue calls were rejected. But the while loop, after the await, will check the queue again. If there's an item and an idle worker, it dispatches. If the queue is now empty (because the while loop processed it), or there's no idle worker, it exits.\n\nWait, but the submit happens DURING the await. So after the await completes, the queue has the new item and an idle worker is available. The while loop continues, shifts and dispatches, then exits when the queue empties. So the simple guard actually works—if submit happens during an await, the while loop hasn't exited yet, so it naturally processes the new item before releasing the guard. Checking another edge case where a worker becomes available during the await—if getIdleWorker returns null while a dispatch is in flight, the queue item stays put until that worker finishes and processQueue runs again from the worker-ready event.\n\nNow tracing through what happens if both a new item gets submitted and a second worker connects while the first dispatch is still pending: the queue gets [B], processQueue tries to run but the guard blocks it since dispatching is already true, then when the await completes and the loop continues, it finds B in the queue and W2 ready to take it.\n\nThe guard pattern handles this correctly. Let me code it up.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a potential issue with recursive calls to processQueue from within dispatchToWorker—when assignment fails and the item gets re-queued, the recursive processQueue call would hit the guard and return early, but the outer while loop should still pick up the re-queued item on the next iteration.\n\nNow I'm looking at the assign method to understand what happens when it fails. The method checks if a worker is idle, marks it as executing, removes it from the idle pool, and sends the assignment. If the send fails, the worker stays marked as executing even though it's not actually running anything. so I'll add a guard flag to prevent concurrent execution, remove the recursive call since the while loop handles it, and keep `unshift` for maintaining queue order since the guard ensures only one processQueue runs at a time. so only one call to dispatchToWorker happens at a time, so unshift is fine.\n\nActually, with the guard, the concurrent race can't happen at all! Only one processQueue loop runs at a time, so:\n- Only one getIdleWorker/shift/dispatch happens at a time\n- No two calls can grab the same idle worker\n- No unshift ordering corruption\n\nThe fix is simply adding the dispatching guard.\n\nWhen dispatchToWorker fails and re-queues the item, the recursive processQueue call gets blocked by the guard, but that's fine—the while loop continues and tries the next worker, or exits if none are available. The item stays queued for when a worker becomes ready. The busy handler also calls processQueue asynchronously, and with the guard in place, it'll just be a no-op if processQueue is already running.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13351,"cache_read_input_tokens":19261,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13351},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aefd2344-322a-4270-982f-2978aca96abe","uuid":"40b0aa84-67d3-4279-a0d1-552bcc7f96a2"}
